<HL> Imports Again Top Fuel-Efficient List Of Cars, EPA Says </HL>
<AUTHOR> Paulette Thomas (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> HMC F GM </CO>
<IN> AUT MON </IN>
<G> EPA </G>
<DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cars made overseas, but sold through U.S. dealerships, again topped the list of the 10 most fuel-efficient cars, according to the Environmental Protection Agency.

   The 1989 Geo Metro, from General Motors Corp.'s imported-vehicle division, topped the list for best mileage, with 53 miles per gallon in the city, and 58 miles per gallon on the highway.
No cars manufactured in the U.S. were among the top 10.

   Although the EPA has reported the fuel-economy data since 1974, the information lacks the impact it did during periods of fuel shortages.
"It certainly isn't as big a factor as it was five or 10 years ago," said Dennis Sperduto, auto-industry analyst at Argus Research Corp., New York.
"It depends on the buyer.
Someone with money isn't going to care about fuel economy these days."

   Cars marketed as the Geo Metro is have altered the way the EPA breaks down the fuel-economy lists.
Because of the increasing number of auto lines that spring, as the Geo Metro does, from U.S.-foreign joint ventures, the EPA no longer bothers to compile its list of the most fuel-efficient U.S. cars.
"The EPA stopped producing one because of the increasing confusion over what a domestic car is," a spokesman said.
The Geo Metro is manufactured by Japan's Suzuki Motor Co.

   U.S. auto manufacturers must meet minimum fuel-economy standards, as set by an arm of the Department of Transportation, but U.S. cars are heading back to their gas-guzzling days.
General Motors, for example, has argued that Americans want to buy larger luxury models, and has asked the agency to relax the minimum standard to 26 miles per gallon from 27.5 miles per gallon for the average mileage of all the cars it sells.

   The fuel-economy estimates evolved from the EPA fuel-emission tests to measure pollution control.
Manufacturers submit their test data, and the EPA confirms about 30% of the results in its own laboratory.

   Other high-mileage cars listed by the EPA include the Honda Civic CRX HF, at 50 city and 56 highway miles per gallon; a Geo Metro Lsi at 46 city and 50 highway; a Honda Civic CRX IF at 45 city and 52 highway, a Ford Festiva at 39 city and 48 highway, and a Daihatsu Charade listed at 38 city and 42 highway.

   Taking honors for the worst fuel economy was an Aston Martin Lagonda with a 5.3-liter engine and an automatic transmission.
It gets eight miles per gallon in the city and 11 on the highway.

</TEXT>
