<HL> Ford Won't Ask U.S. to Relax Rules On Fuel Economy </HL>
<AUTHOR> Joseph B. White (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> F </CO>
<IN> AUT </IN>
<DATELINE> MONROE, Mich.  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time in three years, Ford Motor Co. won't ask the federal government to relax its fuel economy standards for cars, the head of Ford's automotive operations said.

   "We are planning to meet the 27.5" miles-per-gallon corporate average fuel economy (CAFE) standard for 1989-model cars, Philip E. Benton Jr., president of Ford Automotive Group, said yesterday after presenting a quality award to Ford's Monroe metal stamping plant.

   Ford will hit the 27.5 miles-per-gallon target by offering more efficient engines and by heavily promoting sales of its smaller cars, Mr. Benton said.
The more high-mileage small domestic cars like the Escort that Ford sells, the higher its company-wide average miles-per-gallon rating, under the federal rules.
Meeting the 27.5 fuel standard probably will mean "rebates for Escorts," a company spokesman said.

   Ford also will use credits it has banked by exceeding mileage standards in previous years to boost its fuel economy figures for 1989, if necessary, Mr. Benton said.

   For the past three model years, Ford has joined General Motors Corp. and a consortium of auto importers in asking the government to ease the so-called CAFE standards for cars.
In response to the auto makers' appeals, the National Highway Transportation Safety Administration rolled back the target to 26 miles per gallon from 27.5 for the 1986, 1987 and 1988 model years.
Chrysler Corp. opposed those efforts.

   GM earlier this month asked the government to re-evaluate the 27.5 miles-per-gallon target for 1989 and 1990, saying it put full-line auto makers like GM at a disadvantage.

   The government can fine auto makers that fail to meet the higher fuel economy standard.
That issue came up earlier this month when a federal appeals court decision in Washington D.C. effectively overturned an effort by the Environmental Protection Agency to retroactively boost its estimates of the average gas mileage of Ford and GM cars for the 1980 to 1984 model years.

   But a Ford spokesman said the company doesn't expect to pay any fine in connection with that ruling.

</TEXT>
