<CAPTION>  Photo, map; MAP: Wes Killingbeck - Mercury News; SOUTHERN PACIFIC DERAILMENT;
PHOTO: Associated Press; RAIL CARNAGE -- Several Southern Pacific cars, some
burned, lie crushed under a Highway 101 underpass after derailing Sunday at
Seacliff. A portion of 101 remains closed.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  RAILROAD; ACCIDENT; FIRE; CAUSE; ROAD; CLOSING; CHEMICAL; HAZARDOUS-MATERIAL  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  A Southern Pacific train threw sparks for 20 miles and started more than 30
fires before it derailed on the Ventura County coast Sunday.;    But no one
aboard noticed because the train didn't have a caboose and the nearest rail
heat sensors were miles away.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  OVERHEATED TRAIN SET 30 FIRES BEFORE DERAILMENT  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Mercury News Staff Writer Tom Philp and wire services contributed to this
report.
Additional information attached to the end of this article.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Fourteen freight cars eventually slammed into each other in a spectacular
accident that will keep Highway 101 closed into today or beyond as officials
clean up toxic chemicals and check an overpass the cars rammed.;
California's second serious train derailment in two weeks renewed calls for
better regulation of how toxic materials are shipped.;    "The train cars just
broke apart like over-ripe melons," said Terrence Gilday, Ventura County
environmental health manager. "We have drums of hazardous material all over
the place, and it's still releasing fumes. It's going to be a mess for a
while.";    Traffic jams caused by the closing of 10 miles of Highway 101, the
main coastal link between Northern and Southern California, continued Monday
with reports of some detoured motorists being delayed up to 12 hours. Some
reported feeling ill from the toxic cloud.;    Hazardous-material experts
wearing blue "space suit" protective gear tried Monday to neutralize at least
15 ruptured drums containing aqueous hydrazine, a component of rocket fuel.;
 Vacationing campers and hundreds of residents in the posh oceanfront
community of Seacliff remained evacuated Monday. Three people were treated for
nausea after breathing fumes from the spilled hydrazine.;    One of those who
complained was Rep. Barbara Boxer, D-San Rafael, who reported feeling "ill and
nauseous" after driving by the derailment site.;    Ironically, Boxer had
called for a congressional hearing Wednesday on train safety issues because of
the derailment two weeks ago in the Sacramento River headwaters.;    The
Seacliff accident was almost a repeat performance of July 14, when another
Southern Pacific derailment dumped poison into the river, killing all life in
a 40-mile stretch of one of Northern California's most pristine trout
streams.;    Less of a threat;  Officials said the Ventura County derailment
doesn't pose the same environmental threat.;    Investigators suspect that the
Sunday derailment was caused by a frozen wheel bearing that got so hot it
melted the axle. A wheel then fell off, and witnesses said the dragging
container car spewed sparks and threw gravel for miles.;    Ventura County
firefighters responded to some 30 spot fires left in the northbound train's
wake, from Camarillo almost to the Santa Barbara County line.;    But
apparently the engineer couldn't detect the problem from the front of the
39-car train, which was three-quarters of a mile long.;    Emergency crews
responding to the fires had difficulty contacting the train crew, Gilday said.
"It was a matter of the train being faster than communication.";    Train
workers blame the accident on the lack of a caboose, which Southern Pacific
began phasing out seven years ago in an attempt to reduce the number of crew
members required on each train.;    Supports caboose;  "No one can refute the
fact that if there had been a caboose on the train, the accident would have
been avoided," said J. P. Jones, legislative director of the United
Transportation Union.;    In place of staffed cabooses, Southern Pacific says
it has placed heat detectors at intervals along its tracks to sense overheated
wheels and sparks. The ill-fated train passed one sensor 36 miles before the
derailment, and there was no sign of a wheel problem, spokesman Bob Hoppe
said. The train derailed two miles before the next detector could have warned
the engineer of a problem, Hoppe said.;    Southern Pacific, criticized for
taking an hour to notify the state Office of Emergency Services after the
Sacramento River spill, took one hour and 40 minutes to call the OES on
Sunday. By that time, local fire and environmental safety officials had
already evacuated residents and campers.;    The train carried 76 55-gallon
drums of diluted hydrazine. A brief breath of the ammonia-like chemical can
cause nausea and burning eyes. Longer-term exposure can cause burns, damage
internal organs and ultimately result in death, said Jay Young, a chemical
health and safety consultant.;    'Wonderful tear gas';  "Basically, your red
blood cells go to pieces," Young said. "If that stuff is blowing over a
highway, the road should be closed. It would make a wonderful tear gas if it
weren't so deadly dangerous.";    The highway may not reopen until Wednesday,
depending on cleanup and an assessment of the Highway 101 overpass damaged in
the derailment. It is suspected that as the heavy freight cars tumbled
underneath the freeway, they weakened the bridge supports.;    A decision
won't be made until late today at the earliest, "but it will probably be
Wednesday," said Cornell Kimball of the California Department of
Transportation.;    The derailment disrupted passenger service on the main San
Francisco-Los Angeles route, and Amtrak bused passengers between Santa Barbara
and Los Angeles, spokesman Bruce Heard said. Six Amtrak trains ply the route
daily, with several hundred people on board each train. It was unknown when
service might resume.;    Patricia M. Eckert, president of the California
Public Utilities Commission, arrived at the Seacliff site Monday afternoon for
a briefing and said she was "extremely concerned" about the second toxic spill
in two weeks.;    Procedure probe;  The PUC is investigating whether Southern
Pacific was following proper procedure for transporting hazardous materials.;
  The emergency came virtually on the eve of Santa Barbara's annual Old
Spanish Days fiesta, which draws up to 100,000 visitors daily. The five-day
celebration starts Wednesday.;    "Right now, we are virtually marooned," said
a fiesta spokeswoman, Diana Vandervoort. "We depend on the tourists, and a lot
of our suppliers come from the Los Angeles area.;    "It may be just a local
community party this year."; DETOUR DATA; Information on the status of Highway
101 near the derailment site is available by calling (408) 436-1404.; WHY
LATEST SPILL WAS LESS DEVASTATING; The Sunday derailment in Ventura County was
bad -- but not as devastating as the Sacramento River spill two weeks ago.
Here's why:; (box)The Ventura spill occurred on land, contaminating only
soil.; (box)Emergency crews responded within minutes to the Ventura spill,
evacuating residents within one hour. Sacramento River residents were
evacuated 12 hours after the accident.; (box)Ventura County had an emergency
hazardous spill plan. Siskiyou County did not.; (box)Only about 800 gallons of
toxic chemical spilled Sunday. More than 13,000 gallons of a
herbicide/pesticide flowed into the Sacramento River.; (box)Hydrazine, the
chemical that spilled in Ventura County, is well-known and researched. Vapam,
the weed killer that went into the river, is little understood.; (box)The
train car carrying hydrazine was labeled hazardous. The tanker carrying Vapam
was not.  </TEXT>
