<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Japanese auto companies once again crowded
U.S. manufacturers off the U.S. government's list of new cars
and new trucks with the highest gas mileage.
   In tests of coming 1992 models by the Environmental
Protection Agency, the Geo Metro XFi ranked as the most
fuel-efficient car for the sixth year in a row. The
three-cylinder subcompact, made by Suzuki Motor Co. and sold
by General Motors Corp., got 53 miles per gallon in city
driving and 58 mpg in highway driving.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Second place was earned by a version of the 1992 Honda
Civic Hatchback VX, sporting a new "lean-burn" technology
that uses less fuel per combustion stroke. It got 48 mpg in
the city and 55 mpg on the highway.
   The remainder of high-mileage autos on the list also are
Japanese imports, though some Honda Civics will be assembled
in Canada. The list names certain versions -- all with
five-speed manual transmission -- of the Geo Metro, Honda
Civic and Suzuki Swift, with fuel economy ratings that ranged
down to 39 mpg in the city and 43 mpg on the highway.
   The annual rankings come as U.S. auto makers are lobbying
the Senate to block a bill by Sen. Richard Bryan (D., Nev.)
that would require fleets of new cars to get an average of 40
mpg by model year 2001. The current standard is 27.5 mpg.
   Among light-duty trucks, a Suzuki Samurai Soft-Top 4WD
topped the fuel efficiency list. It gets 28 mpg in the city
and 29 mpg on the highway. Suzuki, Geo and Subaru trucks
filled out the list, with mileage ranging from 24 mpg to 28
mpg in the city and 27 mpg to 29 mpg on the highway.
   The car with the worst fuel economy on the road for 1992
will be the 12-cylinder Italian Lamborghini DB132/Diablo,
which gets only nine mpg in city driving and 14 mpg on the
highway and carries a stiff U.S. gas-guzzler tax of $6,400 a
vehicle. Congress this year doubled the amount of gas-guzzler
taxes, which are charged on any car getting less than 22.5
mpg.
   Three Dodge truck models took the honors for gas-guzzling
light-duty trucks, rating nine mpg in the city and 13 mpg on
the highway. Gas-guzzler taxes aren't charged on trucks.
   Comparison shoppers can find a complete list of
fuel-economy ratings for new cars in an EPA guide that is
expected to be available at dealerships in about two months.
In addition, mileage ratings are listed on window stickers of
new vehicles. The EPA has been ranking cars for fuel economy
since 1974.
</TEXT>
