<HL> Transport Chief Urges Easier Rules For Gas Mileage </HL>
<AUTHOR> Joseph B. White (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> F GM C </CO>
<IN> AUT </IN>
<G> TRN CNG </G>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. secretary of transportation said he wants a relaxation of congressionally mandated fuel-economy standards for cars, a move that would clear the way for auto makers to sell bigger cars and earn larger profits.

   Calling current fuel-economy rules "a dinosaur that should be extinct," the official, James Burnley, sided with the auto industry in the battle over efforts to require improved gas mileage.

   Mr. Burnley said the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration proposes to lower the federal gas-mileage target for 1989 and 1990 model cars, possibly to as low as 26.5 miles a gallon.
The current target is an average of 27.5 miles a gallon for each car maker's fleet.

   Under current rules, an auto maker that fails to meet the target could be fined as much as $5 a car for every one-tenth of a mile that its fleet's average falls below the mileage target.
In other words, if a car maker missed the standard by one-tenth of a mile and sold 3.5 million cars, it could be fined $17.5 million.

   In a statement, Mr. Burnley linked the target-lowering proposal, made in response to a petition for relief filed by General Motors Corp., to the preservation of jobs.
GM, the largest auto maker, says it couldn't meet the 1989 target without significant layoffs and production cuts.
A group of foreign auto makers also petitioned for relief.

   "I want to make very sure that we're not putting U.S. jobs at risk over the next two years," Mr. Burnley said.

   Advocates of tougher fuel-economy regulation denounced the proposed relaxation.

   "When we need to decrease consumption of fossil fuels to reduce carbon dioxide and the 'greenhouse effect,' we need to be headed toward doubling fuel economy standards, not rolling them back," said Clarence Ditlow, executive director of the Washington-based Center for Auto Safety.
The center has filed suits challenging earlier Transportation Department orders that relaxed the fuel-economy standards for the 1986, 1987 and 1988 model years.

   The latest round in the years-long debate over fuel economy comes as GM and Ford Motor Co., the second largest U.S. auto maker, are scrambling to meet a surge in demand for their larger models.
Selling more of these cars would mean bigger profits.
It also would mean missing the fuel-economy standard.

   Ford has said it could meet the current standard for 1989 cars only by introducing major sales incentives on its smaller models.
This is because customers "are asking for bigger cars," a Ford spokeswoman said.

   GM, meanwhile, wants to build larger cars to help reverse a slide in market share that followed its decision to reduce the size of its luxury models.
That move was part of GM's effort to meet fuel-economy standards in the early 1980s.
The company has predicted that the average fuel efficiency of its 1990 model cars will drop to 26.8 miles a gallon from its current 27.3 miles.

   Chrysler Corp., meanwhile, apparently has decided not to oppose GM's petition for relief, though it has done so in the past.
Chrysler, a spokesman said, already meets the mileage target.
"It's not an issue," he said.

   The highway traffic safety agency has scheduled a hearing on its gas-mileage proposal for Sept. 14.
The agency is also seeking public comment on the proposed change for the 1989 model year until Sept. 15.

