<LEADPARA>  MINIVANS have taken a chunk of what was once a solely station wagon market,
but wagons are back in a big way for '92 with sizes ranging from the compact
Ford Escort to the full-size Buick Roadmaster Estate.;   Ford Escort LX Wagon  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Drive  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  WAGONS HIT THE '92 TRAIL IN A WIDE RANGE OF SIZES
VARIATIONS INCLUDE COMPACTS AND 'LAND YACHTS'  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Automotive magazine journalists Mike Anson and Steven Parker host radio's
"America on the Road" on the Mutual Broadcasting System. Their column appears
in Drive twice monthly.; America on the Road  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The Ford Escort LX wagon body is topping a reliable Mazda Protege
front-wheel-drive chassis. Escort styling reflects the aerodynamic style of
the successful Ford Taurus -- Escort's been dubbed a "baby Taurus" by some --
and combines the small size of the Escort with the extra space of a station
wagon.;   The Escort is powered by Ford's 1.9-liter, four-cylinder engine that
delivers 88 horsepower but feels much stronger. It carries a fuel-economy
rating of 25 miles per gallon in the city and 33 miles per gallon on the
highway. The Escort price is as attractive as its styling. A basic Escort LX
Wagon has a base price of less than $10,000. Fully equipped, it's still under
$12,000.;   Honda Accord;   Despite its foreign roots, the Accord station
wagon is built in Marysville, Ohio, and many of them are actually exported to
Japan -- where they're considered a status symbol. The Accord sedan is the
most popular car in America and Honda is waiting for its two Accord wagon
models, the well-equipped DX and more luxurious LX, to catch on with the same
intensity. There are two variations of the 2.2-liter, four-cylinder engine.
The "base-level" delivers 125 horsepower, and there's the more powerful and
slightly more expensive 140-horsepower version. Test drive both models and see
which version best suits your needs.;   The Accord wagon offers safety and
convenience -- it's the first Accord to offer a driver's-side air bag and the
wagon's tailgate extends all the way down to the rear bumper. When it's open,
this provides a low "lift-over" height for easy cargo loading. The price
ranges from $17,400 to $20,000, but this model even has air conditioning as
standard equipment.;   Subaru Legacy;   The Subaru is built in a plant shared
with Isuzu in Lafayette, Ind. Subaru has a strong reputation for building
durable, all-wheel-drive station wagons and the Legacy continues this
tradition. The wagon is available with either front-wheel drive, suitable for
everyday driving situations, or all-wheel drive, when extra traction is needed
in inclement weather.;   Power is supplied by a 2.2-liter, four-cylinder
engine rated at 130 horsepower. EPA fuel economy is 20 miles per gallon in the
city and 26 miles per gallon on the highway. Weighing in at just over 3,000
pounds, the Legacy wagon is very sure-footed, corners well and holds the road,
even in slippery conditions.;   Subaru cars have a reputation for styling
that's definitely out of the mainstream, but they are also noted for being
well-constructed and a good value. Prices for the all-wheel-drive version of
the Subaru Legacy station wagon range from $15,000 to $20,000 for the
top-of-the-line LSi model.;   Ford Taurus/Mercury Sable;   For the first time
in its '92 models, Ford has made the V-6 engine standard. The base engine is a
3.0-liter V-6, but we think you should also test drive the larger, more
powerful 3.8-liter V-6. We also recommend the optional anti-lock brakes. A
driver's-side air bag has been standard since the 1990 model year.;   Although
Ford has been able to showcase its expertise with electronic instrument
panels, you should also consider the more familiar and more readable analog
instruments. The Taurus and Sable wagons offer good size and value for a
reasonable price -- starting at $15,000 and moving up to about $20,000
depending on optional equipment.;   Buick Roadmaster; Estate Wagon;
Measuring more than 18 feet long and weighing in at a hefty 4,500 pounds,
Buick's Roadmaster Estate Wagon is the largest passenger car made in America.
It's an updated version of a traditional American station wagon and even has
the traditional rear-facing third seat made popular in the classic station
wagons of the '50s and '60s.;   This land yacht is powered by GM's 5.7-liter,
V-8 engine that has been updated with fuel injection for improved fuel
economy. It manages to deliver 16 miles per gallon in the city and 25 miles
per gallon on the highway.;   This is a luxury cruiser with real towing
ability. Anti-lock brakes are standard along with a driver's-side air bag.
Prices range from $23,000 to $25,000, depending on options.  </TEXT>
