worked until after midnight, setting up for today's operation, he said. It's
not known when the work will be finished.;    Weary fire crews from Ventura
and Oxnard County were to be given a break in cleanup efforts today, with
firefighters with toxic conduct expertise due in from Los Angeles and Santa
Barbara County, Taylor said.;    Fumes from the toxic hydrazine still hang
over the spill area, he said. Some 300 residents evacuated from Seacliff won't
be able to return home until the full cleanup is completed, Taylor said.;
The derailed SP train threw sparks for 20 miles and started more than 30 fires
before the derailment.;    14 freight cars involved;  But no one aboard
noticed because the train didn't have a caboose and the nearest rail heat
sensors were miles away.;    Fourteen freight cars eventually slammed into
each other in a spectacular accident.;    California's second serious train
derailment in two weeks, both by Southern Pacific, renewed calls for better
regulation of how toxic materials are shipped.;    "The train cars just broke
apart like over-ripe melons," said Terrence Gilday, Ventura County
environmental health manager. "We have drums of hazardous material all over
the place, and it's still releasing fumes. It's going to be a mess for a
while.";    Three people were treated for nausea after breathing fumes from
the spilled hydrazine.;    One of those who complained was Rep. Barbara Boxer,
D-San Rafael, who reported feeling "ill and nauseous" after driving by the
derailment site.;    Ironically, Boxer had called for a congressional hearing
Wednesday on train safety issues because of the derailment two weeks ago in
the Sacramento River headwaters.;    Repeat performance; The Seacliff accident
was almost a repeat performance of July 14, when another Southern Pacific
derailment dumped poison into the river, killing all life in a 40-mile stretch
of one of Northern California's most pristine trout streams.;    Officials
said the Ventura County derailment doesn't pose the same environmental
threat.;    Investigators suspect the Sunday derailment was caused by a frozen
wheel bearing that got so hot it melted the axle. A wheel then fell off, and
witnesses said the dragging container car spewed sparks and threw gravel for
miles.;    Ventura County firefighters responded to some 30 spot fires left in
the northbound train's wake, from Camarillo almost to the Santa Barbara County
line.;    But apparently the engineer couldn't detect the problem from the
front of the 39-car train, which was three-quarters of a mile long.;
Emergency crews responding to the fires had difficulty contacting the train
crew, Gilday said. "It was a matter of the train being faster than
communication.";    Train workers blame the accident on the lack of a caboose,
which Southern Pacific began phasing out seven years ago in an attempt to
reduce the number of crew members required on each train.;    "No one can
refute the fact that if there had been a caboose on the train, the accident
would have been avoided," said J. P. Jones, legislative director of the United
Transportation Union.;    Heat detectors;  In place of staffed cabooses,
Southern Pacific says it has placed heat detectors at intervals along its
tracks to sense overheated wheels and sparks. The ill-fated train passed one
sensor 36 miles before the derailment, and there was no sign of a wheel
problem, spokesman Bob Hoppe said. The train derailed two miles before the
next detector could have warned the engineer of a problem, Hoppe said.;
Southern Pacific, criticized for taking an hour to notify the state Office of
Emergency Services after the Sacramento River spill, took one hour and 40
minutes to call the OES on Sunday. By that time, local fire and environmental
safety officials had already evacuated residents and campers.;    The train
carried 76 55-gallon drums of diluted hydrazine. A brief breath of the
ammonia-like chemical can cause nausea and burning eyes. Longer-term exposure
can cause burns, damage internal organs and ultimately result in death, said
Jay Young, a chemical health and safety consultant.;    "Basically, your red
blood cells go to pieces," Young said. "If that stuff is blowing over a
highway, the road should be closed. It would make a wonderful tear gas if it
weren't so deadly dangerous.";    The highway may not reopen until Wednesday,
depending on cleanup and an assessment of the Highway 101 overpass damaged in
the derailment. It is suspected that as the heavy freight cars tumbled
underneath the freeway, they weakened the bridge supports.;    A decision
won't be made until late today at the earliest, "but it will probably be
Wednesday," said Cornell Kimball of the California Department of
Transportation.;    Passengers disrupted;  The derailment disrupted passenger
service on the main San Francisco-Los Angeles route, and Amtrak bused
passengers between Santa Barbara and Los Angeles, spokesman Bruce Heard said.
Six Amtrak trains ply the route daily, with several hundred people on board
each train. It was unknown when service might resume.  </TEXT>
