<HEAD>Government Sets Light Truck CAFE for 1992</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fuel economy standards for 1992 light trucks will
stay the same as for 1991 models, the government said Friday.
   Auto companies opposed tougher standards for 1992, saying people
are buying larger trucks that bring average fuel economy down.
Environmental groups had argued that the standard should be tougher.
   ``The biggest thing we can do to curb global warming is to
improve the fuel efficiency of our cars and light trucks,'' said
Sierra Club spokesman Dan Becker in Washington, D.C.
   The corporate average fuel economy standard for 1992 light
trucks will be 20.2 miles per gallon, the same as the 1991 CAFE
requirement and up from 20 mpg this year, the National Highway
Traffic Safety Administration said.
   In addition to setting a CAFE requirement for cars, currently
27.5 miles per gallon, NHTSA annually sets a light truck standard
applying to pickup trucks, vans and utility vehicles that weigh up
to 8,500 pounds.
   NHTSA decided manufacturers couldn't achieve significant
improvements for 1992 through technological or marketing changes,
spokesman Jim Herd said.
   Ford Motor Co. backed the lower requirement because larger
trucks are selling faster than smaller, more fuel-efficient ones,
said David L. Kulp, Ford's manager of fuel economy, planning and
compliance.
   ``We felt that the market was going to hold us at this kind of
level. There are improvements being made in the trucks, they've
just been offset by some of the shifts to the larger products,''
Kulp said.
   General Motors Corp. spokesman John Anderson said the decision
recognized that tighter standards could reduce trucks' usefulness.
``Trucks have an enormous range of applications, from towing to
agricultural and construction uses,'' he said.
   The Environmental Action Foundation argued on behalf of groups
including the Sierra Club that standards should be raised, to 35
miles per gallon by 2000, said Dru Schmidt-Perkins, environmental
analyst for the group.
   ``They are already 25 percent less efficient than cars,''
Schmidt-Perkins said. ``And for the most part these are not farm
vehicles and not commercial vans, they are minivans and light
pickup trucks which do nothing more than haul briefcases and
groceries.''
</TEXT>
