<BYLINE>GM, Ford Warn Stricter Fuel Economy Standards Would Cost Jobs</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Failure to loosen fuel economy standards for
1989 and 1990 cars will cost American jobs and may drive carbuyers
into the showrooms of foreign manufacturers, the nation's two
largest automakers said Wednesday.
   General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co., at a public hearing,
urged the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration to keep
the mandatory fuel economy level from reverting to 27.5 miles per
gallon in October.
   Both GM and Ford said they could not produce a mix of cars that
would have a corporate average fuel economy, or CAFE, at that
level. Chrysler Corp., the third large U.S. automaker, projected it
will meet or exceed a 27.5 mpg standard next year and did not speak
at the hearing.
   The standard has been set at 26 mpg since 1986 under an
exception allowed by NHTSA.
   The fuel-economy law, adopted in 1975 to reduce imported
petroleum consumption at a time of rapidly rising prices, sets a
maximum level of fuel consumption each automaker's fleet of
passenger cars, on average, must meet.
   ``Ford's inability to meet the 27.5 mpg CAFE standard for 1989
and 1990 is not because of lack of effort, but instead is because
of substantial market and economic changes,'' said Donald Buist,
Ford's director of automotive emissions and fuel economy.
   With gasoline prices averaging below $1 a gallon, larger cars
are selling well as consumers look for luxury and performance
rather than concentrating on mileage, Buist said.
   The corporate average fuel economy is calculated on the basis of
sales, and public demand for less fuel efficient large cars drives
the average up, the automakers said.
   ``Overly stringent CAFE standards restrict domestic production
of larger cars and higher performance engines,'' Buist said.
``Foreign manufacturers, in particular the Japanese, are ready and
willing to meet this consumer demand with vehicles built or sourced
predominately in foreign countries. This could result in the loss
of thousands of U.S. jobs without any appreciable fuel economy
savings.''
   GM presented Transportation Secretary James Burnley with 5,000
letters from employees of and retirees from its Arlington, Texas,
assembly plant, their families and labor leaders urging him to
lower the CAFE standard to 26.5 mpg.
   A 27.5 mpg standard would force cutbacks in big-car production,
resulting in layoffs in Arlington and elsewhere that would cost GM
and its suppliers 60,000 jobs in 1989 and 110,000 jobs in 1990,
said Richard Klimisch, GM's environmental activities executive
director.
   Klimisch said GM has lost in its share of the market because
``we've gone too far with CAFE.''
   ``It doesn't do any good to put in new technology if you can't
sell the cars,'' Klimisch said.
   Opponents of looser standards urged NHTSA to raise the
fuel-economy requirement to 27.5 mpg as the agency has proposed.
   Clarence Ditlow, director of the Center for Auto Safety, a
consumers group, said if the standards were relaxed, ``the domestic
manufacturers would virtually become importers of everything but
large cars, given the projected worldwide glut of auto production
capacity.'' The result, he said, would be the export of U.S. jobs.
   The center proposed raising the standard to 55 mpg by the turn
of the century, beginning at 30 mpg in 1991.
   NHTSA said it expects to issue a rule on the 1989 and 1990
standards within weeks.
   GM said its 1988 average fleet mileage would be 27.5 mpg or 27.6
mpg. Ford projected average fuel economy of 26.5 mpg this year, and
Chrysler said its cars would average 28.5 mpg.
</TEXT>
