<HEADLINE>  MADE IN AMERICA? MAYBE
LAW STRETCHED TO DETERMINE CAR'S BIRTHPLACE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Chart attached at end of article  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     And in Fremont, scores of workers assemble the virtually identical Geo
Prizm and Toyota Corolla. Prizm is a domestic, and Corolla is an import, the
Environmental Protection Agency says.;   These bizarre rulings come from CAFE,
an acronym for Corporate Average Fuel Economy. CAFE is a muddled 16-year-old
federal law that mixes efforts to improve automotive fuel economy with
protecting U.S. auto industry jobs.;   Instead, the law sometimes causes the
loss of American jobs and missed chances to boost fuel efficiency and even
gives Japanese carmakers a business advantage over U.S. competitors, auto
industry executives and union officials agree.;   CAFE's glaring defects are
in the spotlight now because the U.S. Senate is preparing to vote on new CAFE
proposals aimed at increasing fuel economy 32 to 40 percent over the next 10
to 15 years.;   The problems with CAFE reflect the kind of regulatory tangle
that can occur when the government pursues separate and possibly contradictory
goals with a single piece of legislation.;   Here's how CAFE entered such a
regulatory Twilight Zone:;   In 1975, the United Auto Workers union championed
a job-saving provision in the initial CAFE law that embodied something called
the two-fleet rule.;   The rule classifies any car that gets 75 percent or
more of its value from the United States or Canada as "domestic." Any car with
at least 25 percent foreign content is an "import." Both the domestic and
import fleets of any automaker must meet the federal gas-mileage standard, now
27.5 miles per gallon.;   The goal of the two-fleet rule was to protect and
expand small-car production jobs in the United States by preventing U.S.
automakers from importing large numbers of small cars to offset the poor
mileage of its U.S.-built gas guzzlers.;   But as the auto industry has become
increasingly global, U.S. and foreign car companies have used the two-fleet
CAFE mix in ways that were never intended:;   (check) Ford Motor Co. builds
the Mercury Tracer in Mexico and classifies it as domestic. Combining North
American parts with cheap labor meets the federal definition of a domestic
car.;   (check) Ford builds the Ford Crown Victoria and Mercury Grand Marquis,
classic American-style cruisers, in Canada but buys enough foreign parts to
call them imports.;   It's all done in the interest of balancing CAFE
numbers.;   "Whenever you have two different goals in the same law, it forces
people into a position of playing games," said Jerry Curry, head of the
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration. "Do we make parts in the
United States? Do we ship them to the United States? Do we make them in Mexico
and pretend?;   "It's all bad for the American worker," said Curry, whose
agency helps enforce CAFE. "You lose jobs when you out-source" parts to
foreign firms.;   UAW officials believe the CAFE two-fleet provision protected
some small-car jobs -- or at least slowed U.S. automotive job losses. Ford,
for instance, still makes the fuel-sipping Escort in the United States to
offset its larger domestic cars. But unionists also acknowledge the unintended
harm of the regulatory mixture.;   "We think for a while the two-fleet idea
worked," said Alan Reuther, the UAW's top lobbyist in Washington. "But the
companies in some sense started standing CAFE on its head. . . . Now the
gaming is costing jobs.";   Reuther blames the trouble on automakers' conduct
and the CAFE law's specific mileage goal, not the two-fleet provision.;   If
the government required percentage increases in fuel economy for each
company's separate fleets -- as suggested in a number of CAFE revision
proposals pending in Congress -- automakers couldn't play games as easily, he
said.;   The Crown Victoria case is the most glaring example of CAFE gaming.;
 By shifting a few parts from U.S. and Canadian suppliers to a foreign source,
Ford turned the Crown Victoria/Grand Marquis into an import -- even though it
would continue to be made in North America. The company's more fuel-efficient
import fleet could better absorb the bigger car's 18 mpg in the city, 25 mpg
on the highway.;   But adding foreign parts cost domestic jobs. Ford estimates
it had to absorb 500 workers from the switch, and that doesn't include jobs
lost at outside suppliers.;   David Kulp, Ford's fuel economy planning
manager, said the Crown Victoria decision was a tough one caused by continued
consumer interest in the car. If the model could not be shifted to the import
fleet, Kulp said, Ford would have had to restrict or end its production.;
UAW economist Steve Beckman says that in addition to the cost in jobs, the
Crown Victoria shift hurt the nation's automotive fuel efficiency. The CAFE
two-fleet rule allowed Ford to change its parts supply instead of improving
the big car's mileage.;   In addition to causing such painful decisions by
U.S. carmakers, the CAFE rules encourage the Japanese to import auto parts
rather than buy them in the United States.;   Most major Japanese automakers
build cars in the United States, but so far none has a domestic fleet. And for
now, it's in their best interest to continue having only import fleets --
especially as they build larger cars.;   But to continue having only import
fleets, they must keep the content of the cars they build in the United States
below 75 percent domestic. To achieve this goal, American auto parts purchases
must be limited, some Japanese automakers note.;   Much of the trouble from
the CAFE two-fleet rule is caused by the complicated nature of domestic
content. It's hard, in a global industry, to determine which cars and parts
are foreign and which are domestic.;   Is an engine assembled in America from
Japanese parts domestic? Is a car assembled in Mexico from American parts
foreign? And how many of those parts have to be American before the car is
considered domestic?;   The CAFE law is so vague when it comes to defining
domestic and foreign that the EPA, which checks domestic content under CAFE,
has to examine most cases individually.;   One of the strangest examples is
the General Motors-Toyota joint venture factory in Fremont. That's the place
where the same workers make the same car, but GM counts its Geo Prizm model as
domestic and Toyota certifies its Corolla version as imported.;   This CAFE
magic is aided by yet another regulatory flip: Carmakers are allowed to
average the content of any domestically built car with any foreign-made
versions of the same model. Toyota imports Corollas from Japan and Canada, so
the entire U.S. car line's domestic content is less than the estimated 75
percent of the Fremont Corollas.;   Car-line averaging allows the Japanese to
protect their single-fleet advantage under CAFE. It also results in the Honda
Accord, the most popular single car in America and one that has been made for
years in Marysville, Ohio, being called an "import.";   Even though only about
a third of Accords sold in America are made in Japan, it's enough to make the
whole fleet imported.; CAFE QUIRK; U.S. fuel economy rules have spawned some
strange side; effects. On example: A quintessential Americcan car like the;
Ford Crown Victoria is classfied as an import for 1992. Why?; Because Ford
