<HEAD>Fuel Economy Standard Set at 26.5 mpg for 1989 Models</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf background before penultimate graf pvs. A
version moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley today
told automakers they must achieve an average fuel economy of 26.5
miles per gallon for 1989-model cars _ higher than required this
year but less than mandated under a law Burnley has the power to
change.
   He said his action, cutting 1.0 mpg off the standard Congress
told manufacturers to meet for 1989 models, was designed to help
the U.S. auto industry compete abroad.
   Each automaker is required to post an average fuel economy of at
least 26.0 mpg for all of its 1988 models. That has been the
standard for the last three model years.
   General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co. had said they could not
meet the 27.5-mpg standard without significant layoffs.
   Burnley, making the announcement this morning, said:
   ``A standard of 27.5 mpg for model year 1989 would have clearly
put our domestic full-line manufacturers at a competitive
disadvantage compared to some foreign manufacturers, especially the
Asians, who have been building only small cars and can easily meet
the fuel economy requirements,''
   Arrayed against the automakers in public hearings last month
were a number of public issues groups, which sought even stricter
fuel-economy standards for reasons ranging from conserving gasoline
to reducing carbon-dioxide emissions.
   The fuel-economy law was adopted in 1975 to reduce gasoline
consumption at a time of rapidly rising prices.
   The law set a goal of 27.5 mpg beginning in 1985 but allowed the
Transportation Department, through the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration, to alter the standard.
   It was that provision that enabled the department to set the
standard at 26.0 mpg beginning in 1986 and at 26.5 mpg for the 1989
model year.
   Both GM and Ford had said a 27.5 mpg standard would have caused
layoffs at their auto plants because they would have had to cut
back on production of larger, less fuel-efficient cars.
   Ultimately, the job losses to the auto industry and its
suppliers would have numbered in the hundreds of thousands, GM and
Ford said.
   GM said Burnley's decision ``was in the best interest of
American workers and consumer choice'' and called the 1975 law
``outdated.''
   Ford said the agency's decision ``recognizes that consumer
preferences resulting from low fuel prices have placed a
particularly heavy burden on our efforts to comply with the 27.5
mpg standard.''
   Chrysler Corp. said it would exceed a 27.5 mpg standard and
complained that ``a meaningful gasoline tax would eliminate the
need for a CAFE-like regulatory system.''
   Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca has taken the position that his
company has successfully met the fuel-economy level set by Congress
and federal regulators should not change the rules to help
companies that have been less successful in making fuel-efficient
cars.
   The Center for Auto Safety, a consumers group often at odds with
the automakers and their regulators, said it intends to file a
lawsuit seeking to force NHTSA to allow the standard to return to
27.5 mpg.
   Burnley's decision ``is another cave-in by the Reagan
administration,'' said Clarence Ditlow, the center's director. ``It
is going to cost U.S. jobs as GM and Ford continue to make small
cars abroad.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>

