<HL> Mileage Ruling
May Raise Penalty
For Ford and GM
---
By Robert E. Taylor
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 12/03/86</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> F GM
AUTOS, AUTO PARTS (AUT)
ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (EPA)
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS) </IN>
<DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court here ruled that the Environmental Protection Agency must recalculate fuel economy figures for vehicles made since 1980 in a way that would result in increased federal penalties against Ford Motor Co. and General Motors Corp.

   The Center for Auto Safety, an industry watchdog group based here, said the decision could cost General Motors $250 million and Ford $50 million in penalties for failing to meet U.S. mileage standards.

   The ruling came in a challenge by the auto safety center to a June 1985 decision by the EPA to retroactively boost its estimates of vehicles' gas mileage.
The agency said the 1985 adjustments compensated for changes in testing procedures that had lowered mileage estimates.
Clarence Ditlow, director of the auto safety center, calculated that these changes had freed GM and Ford from about $500 million in penalties.

   In court, the center argued that the EPA must adjust its calculations for changes that increased fuel mileage as well as those that depressed it.
The three-judge panel agreed that the EPA must make adjustments to reflect that the agency tested cars with about 4,000 miles on them in 1975, and as much as 10,000 miles in later years.
Evidence shows that fuel economy generally increases in a new car until it has been driven about 25,000 miles, the court said.

   In Detroit, a GM spokesman said: "We have just received the court's ruling and until we've had a chance to study it, we won't have anything more to say."
A Ford official said the company wouldn't have an immediate comment.

   Chrysler Corp., the other large U.S. auto maker, isn't affected by the ruling because it has complied with the fuel-efficiency mandates.
Chrysler, in fact, has opposed demands by Ford and GM that federal officials relax standards or boost fleet test scores.

   The center's Mr. Ditlow called the ruling "a major victory."
He said, "Ford and GM will now have to hire engineers to meet the fuel-efficiency standards like Chrysler did, rather than rely on lawyers and lobbyists to lower the standards."

   Though the decision would penalize Ford and GM, the companies are expected to be able to trim their liability with credits for beating the 1987 and 1988 requirements for fleet fuel economy.
The Transportation Department recently lowered that requirement to 26 miles per gallon from 27.5 mpg.
The auto safety center's estimates of increased penalties don't take the credits into account.

   EPA officials didn't have any immediate comment on the decision.

</TEXT>
</DOC>

