<HEAD>Advocacy Group Says 1990 Fuel Economy Standard to Stay High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal transportation officials have decided
the 1990 fuel-economy standards should remain at the previous year's
26.5 miles per gallon, says a private auto-safety advocacy group
that wants a higher ceiling.
   The Transportation Department and National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration would neither confirm nor deny Thursday's assertion
by the Washington-based Center for Auto Safety.
   The two agencies administer the corporate average fuel economy,
or CAFE, standards.
   Meanwhile, transportation secretary-designate Samuel Skinner said
he has yet to form a judgment on fuel economy.
   Center Director Clarence Ditlow said he learned of the decison
from sources in the Transportation Department's rule-making office,
the Energy Department, General Motors Corp. and Chrysler Corp.
   He disclosed the 26.5 mpg figure in a letter asking President
Bush to intervene in favor of a tighter fuel-economy sandard.
   The standard would not be formally set until the agency published
a notice in the Federal Register, the government's record of
official actions.
   Neither the Transportation Department nor its subsidiary agency,
the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, would comment on
the assertion.
   The fuel-economy law was adopted in 1975 to reduce gasoline
consumption at a time of rapidly rising oil prices and requires
automakers to design the mix of vehicles in their fleets so that the
average meets or betters the fuel-consumption standard.
   The law set a goal of 27.5 mpg beginning in 1985. However, the
law also allowed the government to reduce that if the higher level
would harm automakers or if it was technologically difficult to
attain.
   If transportation officials failed to act, the standard would
revert to 27.5 mpg, a level GM and Ford Motor Co. have said is
impossible for them to meet without layoffs at big-car plants.
   Skinner said at a hearing Thursday before the Senate Environment
and Public Works Committee that the administration was committed to
an aggressive environmental program, and that the fuel-economy
standards would be ``a key ingredient'' in that program.
   ``I don't consider myself in a position to have prejudged that
issue at all,'' he said.
   The standard was set at 18 mpg for 1978 cars, rose gradually to
27.5 mpg in 1985, and then was lowered to 26 mpg in 1986 at the
request of some of the automakers. It remained at 26 mpg through the
1988 model year.
   The 26.5 mpg level for 1990 is within the range of 26 mpg to 26.7
mpg GM said it could live with.
   Ford said a 26.5 mpg level would be appropriate but called for
``changes that would bring the fuel-economy law more in line with
today's market and economic conditions.''
   Chrysler did not return calls Thursday but has said previously it
could meet the 27.5 mpg goal set by the law.
