<HL> DOT Chief Lowers Gas-Mileage Rule For Autos in 1989 </HL>
<AUTHOR> Laurie McGinley (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> GM </CO>
<IN> AUT ENV </IN>
<G> TRN CNG </G>
<DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation Secretary James Burnley, in a move that delighted U.S. auto makers, lowered the gasoline-mileage requirement for 1989 model passenger cars to 26.5 miles per gallon from the congressionally set standard of 27.5 mpg.

   Mr. Burnley agreed with the domestic auto industry that the tougher standard would cost U.S. jobs and help foreign manufacturers.
Keeping the 27.5 mpg standard for the 1989 model year, which applies to the average mileage for a car maker's entire fleet, "would have clearly put our domestic full-line manufacturers at a competitive disadvantage compared to some foreign manufacturers, especially Asians, who have been building only small cars and can easily meet the fuel-economy requirements," Mr. Burnley said.

   Under the secretary's decision, U.S. auto makers will be able to sell bigger cars and earn larger profits than if the congressional standards hadn't been eased.
The decision angered some environmental groups and congressmen, who argued that it would worsen the nation's already daunting environmental problems.

   The 26.5-mpg requirement, while lower than the standard set by Congress, is slightly higher than the 1988 standard of 26 mpg.
In a 1975 energy-conservation act, Congress set the fuel-economy standards for 1985 and subsequent years at 27.5 mpg.

   But Congress also gave the Transportation Department the authority to change the standard in response to changing economic, technological and energy developments.
The department has made ample use of the authority; it lowered the requirement to 26 mpg for model years 1986, 1987 and 1988.

   The nation's big auto makers applauded Mr. Burnley's decision to relax the 1989 rule.

   General Motors Corp., the nation's biggest auto maker, had asked the Transportation Department to lower the 1989 requirement to 26.5 mpg.
Without the change, GM warned, it would be compelled to cut production and lay off as many as 4,000 workers at a plant in Arlington, Texas, where the company's largest and least fuel-efficient cars are made.

   GM hailed DOT's decision as being "in the best interest of American workers and consumer choice."
But the auto maker added: "The long-term issue is whether Congress will maintain the outdated law which threatens to constrain American auto makers, limit consumer choice of U.S. produced autos and export American jobs."

   Helen O. Petrauskas, vice president of environmental and safety engineering for Ford Motor Co., said: "The rule-making recognizes that consumer preferences, resulting from low fuel prices, have placed a particularly heavy burden on our efforts to comply with the 27.5 mpg standard."

   Advocates of stricter fuel-economy standards denounced Mr. Burnley's decision.
Rep. Tim Wirth (D., Colo.) called the lowering of the standard a "short-sighted effort to promote gas-guzzling dinosaurs" and a setback for U.S. attempts to conserve energy and combat the so-called greenhouse effect, a reference to a warming of the Earth's atmosphere resulting from a build-up of carbon dioxide and other gaseous pollutants.

   Mr. Burnley's decision is "simply wrong," said Clarence Ditlow, director of the Center for Auto Safety, a Washington-based public-interest group often at odds with the auto makers.
He said the auto companies were bluffing in threatening to reduce big-car production in the U.S.

   Mr. Ditlow estimated that the new standard could save the car manufacturers hundreds of millions of dollars in fines that might have been imposed had they failed to meet a tougher standard.

   Even small changes in the fuel-economy target add up to big bucks for the auto makers.
Under the 1975 law, an auto maker that fails to meet the target can be fined as much as $5 for every one-tenth of a mile that its fleet's average falls below the mileage standard.
For example, if a car maker missed the standard by one-tenth of a mile and sold 3.5 million cars, it could be fined $17.5 million.

   The Transportation Department also was criticized for not going far enough in easing the standard.
The Competitive Enterprise Institute, a free-market advocacy group based in Washington, contended that fuel-efficiency standards should be done away with because they increase highway deaths by encouraging the production and sale of lighter cars.
The department has asked Congress to repeal the fuel-efficiency law, but lawmakers have refused to do so.

</TEXT>
</DOC>

