<HEAD>Toyota Exec: Won't Be Able to Tell Import From Domestic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Distinctions between domestic and imported cars
will disappear in this decade, a Toyota Motor Corp. executive said
Thursday, and Ford Motor Co. introduced what it said ushered in the
age of the ``world car.''
   During the 1990s, engineering, design and manufacturing centers
will move freely around the world, focusing in Europe, Asia and
North America, said Robert McCurry, executive vice president of
Toyota Motor Sales U.S.A. Inc., the American marketing arm for
Japan's largest automaker.
   ``Protectionist sentiments will be out of step as trade deficits
begin to balance out,'' McCurry said during the second day of a
three-day media preview of the North American International Auto
Show in Detroit.
   A few hours before he spoke, Ford officials described their
``centers of excellence'' approach that led to the development of
the 1991 Ford Escort. The car was developed in association with
Mazda Motor Corp. of Japan, which provides some of the drivetrain
and other components for the successor to one of the best-selling
cars in the 1980s.
   ``It's a new way of doing business at Ford,'' said company
executive vice president Alex Trotman.
   The ``world car,'' along with its sister vehicle Mercury Tracer,
will be built in Wayne, Mich., and Hermosillo, Mexico, and Ford
expects to sell about 500,000 of them in North America and 950,000
worldwide annually.
   Sales of Escorts have been slipping lately. In 1987 and 1988, it
was the best-selling car in the United States. In 1989, it slipped
to third place, behind the Honda Accord and the Ford Taurus. But
Escort assembly plants were down for part of the year to change
over for new models.
   One of the reasons Ford executives hope the car will catch on is
the impact that it will have on the company's corporate average
fuel economy ratings, or CAFE.
   The federal government mandates that automakers must maintain a
fleet fuel economy average of 27.5 miles per gallon during the 1990
model year or face fines. There has been speculation the minimum
will rise in coming years.
   That gives automakers an impetus to sell small, more
fuel-efficient cars. But there's a gamble involved since small cars
don't provide automakers with as much profit on a per-car basis as
larger cars. And incentives, which have become a part of buying
cars these days, can cut further into the profit margin for each
car sold.
   ``These products don't provide the normal level of profit
because of the volumes we have to maintain for CAFE,'' said Kenneth
Dabrowski, program manager for international and small car programs.
   Ford Chairman Donald Petersen said the new Escort ``couldn't be
more crucial'' to Ford's CAFE rating.
   ``It's the foundation upon which the whole Ford Motor Company
CAFE is built,'' said Ford Division General Manager Tom Wagner.
   In addition to helping the company with its average fuel economy
ratings, auto analysts said Thursday it keeps Ford in the
lower-priced, entry-level market, a market segment that Chrysler
Corp. largely is leaving when it stops production of its Dodge Omni
and Plymouth Horizon cars next month. General Motors Corp. is in
the segment with its Geo line of small cars.
   The Escort-Tracer program involves a $2-billion Ford investment.
The level of Mazda's isn't known, but analysts speculated that it
must be in the neighborhood of $1 billion. Mazda builds its 323
Hatchback off the platform used in the Ford and Mercury vehicles.
</TEXT>
