<TEXT>     Frustrated officials have had to back away from every prediction since
Sunday's midday derailment of 14 cars of a 42-car Los Angeles-to-Oakland
train. Deadly hydrazine, used in rocket fuel, was spilled.;    The wreckage
was strewn along Old Pacific Coast Highway beneath the freeway, closing
Highway 101 and forcing big-rig trucks and other travelers over winding
mountain roads that have added hours to trips.;    Opening date unknown;
"There is no projected opening for the highway. We just don't know," said
Cornell Kimball, a spokesman for the California Department of Transportation.;
   At 5:30 a.m., the drums of hydrazine posing the toxic danger were finally
trucked away from the site of the accident, 60 miles northwest of Los Angeles.
But the leaking hydrazine soaked into the ground.;    "Air and soil tests
showed some hot spots and they cordoned off those areas while they neutralized
the area," said Hoppe. The duration of the neutralizing procedure was unknown,
he said.;    The closing of Highway 101 has been a boon to businesses along
the winding highways being used as detours. In the tiny community of New
Cuyama, travelers have crowded into the Buckhorn Restaurant and the Burger
Barn -- the only restaurants for 50 miles along Highway 166.;    But Santa
Barbara could lose up to $500,000 daily in revenue that had been expected from
tourists who may now stay away from the city's five-day Spanish Days Fiesta,
which began Wednesday.;    There has already been a dramatic drop in tourists,
said Chamber of Commerce President Steve Cushman.;    "I'm not surprised,"
said Hoppe. "But what can I say? We'd like to have that freeway open, too.";
 Truckers suffering;  The California Trucking Association said consumers are
suffering because of the derailment, which has forced about 5,000 truckers to
take longer routes. The extra cost is about $900,000 a day, the organization
said.;    "Trucks carry 98 percent of everything made, grown or sold in
California, and 12 percent of all the truck cargo into or out of the L.A.
basin normally goes down 101 through Seacliff," said CTA spokesman Thomas C.
Schumacher.;    Hoppe would only say, "Clearly we've inconvenienced a lot of
people.";    Four of the derailed cars carried hazardous materials, including
aqueous hydrazine, a jet fuel additive that is a suspected carcinogen and can
be deadly.;    Eight drums of hydrazine burst in the derailment, spewing 440
gallons of the chemical onto the ground.;    The derailment apparently
occurred when a bearing overheated and snapped an axle off a car, triggering a
chain reaction derailment, said Claire Austin, spokeswoman for the Federal
Railroad Administration.;    It was the second Southern Pacific freight train
derailment in California this month. On July 14, a tank car derailed in the
Sacramento River Canyon, spilling a pesticide that killed wildlife along a
45-mile stretch of the river.  </TEXT>
